) function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a general CV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv*{t}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eval{\dv{t}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}}_{t_{1}}=\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\int_{V_{2}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{1}\dd{V}}{t_{2}-t_{1}}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}:=\phi(t_{i},\vec{x})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}:=V(t_{i})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Add 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}$
\end_inset

 to the numerator in the RHS, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\dv{t}\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{1}\dd{V} & =\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{1}\dd{V}}{t_{2}-t_{1}}\\
 & +\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\int_{V_{2}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}}{t_{2}-t_{1}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The first 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim$
\end_inset

 is taking on the difference of two integrals taken on the same domain 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim$
\end_inset

 can exchange with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset

, which leads to a 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{t}$
\end_inset

 inside the integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{1}\dd{V}}{t_{2}-t_{1}} & =\int_{V_{1}}\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\phi_{2}-\phi_{1}}{t_{2}-t_{1}}\dd{V}\\
 & =\int_{V_{1}}\eval{\pdv{\phi}{t}}_{t_{1}}\dd{V}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The second 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim$
\end_inset

 is taking on the difference of two integrals of the same integrand 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

, so the net effect is integrating 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 on the 
\emph on
net incremented volume
\emph default
, which leads to a surface integral:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\frac{\int_{V_{2}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}-\int_{V_{1}}\phi_{2}\dd{V}}{t_{2}-t_{1}} & =\lim_{t_{2}\to t_{1}}\oint_{\partial V_{1}}\frac{\vu{n}_{1}\cdot\cancel{(t_{2}-t_{1})}\vec{u}_{1}^{c}}{\cancel{t_{2}-t_{1}}}\phi_{2}\dd{S}\\
 & =\eval{\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}^{c}\phi\dd{S}}_{t_{1}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}_{1}^{c}:=\vec{u}^{c}(t_{1},\vec{x})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}_{1}:=\vu{n}(t_{1},\vec{x})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Adding them together and dropping 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 leads to the claim.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Material Derivative of An Integral
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, physical laws are stated on material bodies.
 In this section, we denote a material body as 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{m}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $^{m}$
\end_inset

 stands for 
\bar under
m
\bar default
aterial body) to distinguish it from a general control volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{c}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The 
\noun on
material derivative
\noun default
 of an integral
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!material ~!~ of an integral
\end_layout

\end_inset

 taken on 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{c}$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the rate of change of the integral taken on the 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{m}$
\end_inset

 occupying 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{c}$
\end_inset

 at the same time, i.e.
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\DDt{}$"
description "material derivative"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\DDt{}\int_{V^{c}}\phi\dd{V}:=\dv{t}\int_{V^{m}}\phi\dd{V}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
For any CV:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\begin{aligned}\DDt{}\int_{V^{c}}\phi\dd{V} & =\int_{V^{c}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V^{c}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}\phi\dd{S}\\
 & =\dv{t}\int_{V^{c}}\phi\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V^{c}}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\vec{u}-\vec{u}^{c}\right)\phi\dd{S}
\end{aligned}
}\label{eq:DDtOnControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Apply Reynolds transport theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReynoldsTransportTheorem"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dv{t}\int_{V^{m}}\phi\dd{V}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V^{m}}\phi\dd{V}=\int_{V^{m}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V^{m}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}^{m}\phi\dd{S}\label{eq:ReynoldsTransportTheoremOnMaterialBody}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{m}$
\end_inset

 coincides with 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{c}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}^{m}=\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V^{m}$
\end_inset

, there are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\int_{V^{m}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V} & =\int_{V^{c}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}\\
\oint_{\partial V^{m}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}^{m}\phi\dd{S} & =\oint_{\partial V^{m}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}\phi\dd{S}=\oint_{\partial V^{c}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}\phi\dd{S}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Inserting them into the RHS of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReynoldsTransportTheoremOnMaterialBody"

\end_inset

 leads to the 1st line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The 2nd line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 comes immediately by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{V^{c}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}$
\end_inset

 in the 1st line with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V^{c}}\pdv{\phi}{t}\dd{V}=\dv{t}\int_{V^{c}}\phi\dd{V}-\oint_{\partial V^{c}}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}\phi\dd{S}
\]

\end_inset

which comes from Reynolds transport theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ReynoldsTransportTheorem"

\end_inset

, too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Material Derivative at A Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}\phi\in C^{1}(V)$
\end_inset

, then Gauss's divergence theorem can be applied to the surface integral
 in the first line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DDt{}\int_{V}\phi\dd{V}=\int_{V}\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div(\vec{u}\phi)\right)\dd{V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apply the mean value theorem on both sides, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DDt{\ev{\phi}\abs{V}}=\ev{\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div(\vec{u}\phi)}\abs{V}
\]

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\abs{V}:=\int_{V}1\dd{V}\qquad\ev{\cdots}:=\frac{1}{\abs{V}}\int_{V}\cdots\dd{V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}\in C^{1}(V)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\div{\vec{u}}$
\end_inset

 exists every where and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DDt{\abs{V}}=\oint_{V}\dd{V}=\ev{\div{\vec{u}}}\abs{V}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Shrink 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to an infinitesimal body, the variation of the integrand with respect to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 can be ignored, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\DDt{\phi\abs{V}} & \doteq\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}+\div(\vec{u}\phi)\right)\abs{V}\\
\DDt{\abs{V}} & \doteq\left(\div{\vec{u}}\right)\abs{V}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\doteq$
\end_inset

 means the equation is hold when 
\begin_inset Formula $\abs{V}\to0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\div(\vec{u}\phi)=\phi\div\vec{u}+\vec{u}\cdot\grad{\phi}
\]

\end_inset

which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{\phi\abs{V}}-\phi\DDt{\abs{V}}\doteq\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}+\vec{u}\cdot\grad{\phi}\right)\abs{V}\label{eq:DDtOnPhiTimesV}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is then natural to 
\emph on
denote
\emph default
 the parenthesized quantity in the RHS as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\DDt{\phi}=\pdv{\phi}{t}+\vec{u}\cdot\grad{\phi}}\label{eq:DDtAtPoint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is taken as the 
\emph on
definition
\emph default
 of the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!material ~!~ at a point
\end_layout

\end_inset


\noun on
material derivative
\noun default
 at a point.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv*{t}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!local ~
\end_layout

\end_inset


\noun on
local derivative
\noun default
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}\cdot\grad$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
derivative!convective ~
\end_layout

\end_inset


\noun on
convective derivative
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}$
\end_inset

 operates like 
\begin_inset Formula $\pdv{t}$
\end_inset

 when the operand is a product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\DDt{\phi\abs{V}} & =\phi\DDt{\abs{V}}+\abs{V}\DDt{\phi}\\
\DDt{\phi\psi} & =\phi\DDt{\psi}+\psi\DDt{\phi}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The first line comes from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DDtOnPhiTimesV"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DDtAtPoint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), while the second line comes from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\pdv{t}+\vec{u}\cdot\grad\right)$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conservation Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation of Mass
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When applied to a control volume, the law can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{}\int_{V}\rho\dd{V}=0\label{eq:ConservationOfMassWithDDt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation of Momentum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When applied to a control volume, the law can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\DDt{}\int_{V}\vec{u}\rho\dd{V}=\int_{V}\vec{b}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\Tensor{\sigma}\dd{S}
\]

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\vec{b}$"
description "body force per unit volume"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of external body force per unit volume, 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\Tensor{\\sigma}$"
description "stress tensor"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the stress tensor
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tensor!stress ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\vu{n}$"
description "unit outward normal vector"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}$
\end_inset

 is the unit outward normal vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vu{n}\cdot\Tensor{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is thus the vector of external surface force per unit area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stress tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 can always be separately into an isotropic tensor of pressure
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tensor!isotropic ~!~ of pressure
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $-p\Tensor{1}$
\end_inset

 plus a shear stress tensor
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tensor!stress ~!shear ~
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\Tensor{\\tau}$"
description "shear stress tensor"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\Tensor{1}$"
description "unit isotropic tensor"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{1}$
\end_inset

 is the unit isotropic tensor
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
tensor!isotropic ~!unit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 satisfying
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Tensor{1}\cdot\vec{v}=\vec{v}=\vec{v}\cdot\Tensor{1}\qquad\forall\vec{v}
\]

\end_inset

The formula for the law then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{}\int_{V}\vec{u}\rho\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}p\dd{S}=\int_{V}\vec{b}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\Tensor{\tau}\dd{S}\label{eq:ConservationOfMomentumWithDDt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation of Angular Momentum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{\alpha\gamma}=\sigma_{\gamma\alpha}\qquad\forall\alpha,\gamma=1,2,3
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\alpha\gamma}=\tau_{\gamma\alpha}\qquad\forall\alpha,\gamma=1,2,3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservation of Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conservation law of energy is the alias of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:1stLawOfThermodynamics"

\end_inset

.
 When applied to a control volume, it can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\DDt{}\int_{V}\left(e+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2\right)\rho\dd{V} & =\int_{V}j\dd{V}-\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{q}\dd{S}\\
 & +\int_{V}\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\Tensor{\sigma}\cdot\vec{u}\right)\dd{S}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$j$"
description "rate of heat generation per unit volume"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is the rate of heat generation per unit volume.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, if we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{\sigma}=-p\Tensor{1}+\Tensor{\tau}$
\end_inset

 into account, the formula for the law then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned} & \DDt{}\int_{V}\left(e+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2\right)\rho\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdotp\vec{u}\dd{S}\\
= & \int_{V}\left(\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}+j\right)\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\left(\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}-\vec{q}\right)\dd{S}
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:ConservationOfEnergyWithDDt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary of Conservation Laws
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Integral Forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write the three conservation laws (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConservationOfMassWithDDt"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConservationOfMomentumWithDDt"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConservationOfEnergyWithDDt"

\end_inset

) in matrix form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{}\int_{V}U\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{P}\dd{S}=\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{G}\dd{S}+\int_{V}H\dd{V}\label{eq:ConservationLawsWithDDt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in which
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\begin{bmatrix}\rho\\
\vec{u}\rho\\
E\rho
\end{bmatrix}\qquad\vec{P}=\begin{bmatrix}\vec{0}\\
p\Tensor{1}\\
p\vec{u}
\end{bmatrix}\qquad\vec{G}=\begin{bmatrix}\vec{0}\\
\Tensor{\tau}\\
\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}-\vec{q}
\end{bmatrix}\qquad H=\begin{bmatrix}0\\
\vec{b}\\
\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}+j
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Apply the first line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}\int_{V}\cdots\dd{V}$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$E:=e+\\frac{1}{2}\\abs{\\vec{u}}^{2}$"
description "total (internal + kinetic) energy per unit mass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E:=e+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{F}=\vec{u}U+\vec{P}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawsWithDDt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}\pdv{U}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{F}\dd{S}=\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{G}\dd{S}+\int_{V}H\dd{V}\label{eq:ConservationLawsWithoutDDt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the most general form of the governing equations of (continuum)
 fluid dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, if we apply the second line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}\int_{V}\cdots\dd{V}$
\end_inset

 and denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{F}^{c}=\vec{F}-\vec{u}^{c}U=\left(\vec{u}-\vec{u}^{c}\right)\begin{bmatrix}\rho\\
\vec{u}\rho\\
E\rho
\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}\vec{0}\\
p\Tensor{1}\\
p\vec{u}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawsWithDDt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 will then become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dv{t}\int_{V}U\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{F}^{c}\dd{S}=\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{G}\dd{S}+\int_{V}H\dd{V}\label{eq:ConservationLawsForMovingControlVolume}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conservative Differential Form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the integrands in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawsWithoutDDt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are sufficiently smooth, then Gauss's divergence theorem can be applied
 to them, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pdv{U}{t}+\div{\vec{F}}=\div{\vec{G}}+H\label{eq:ConservationLawsInDifferentialForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\pdv{\rho}{t}+\div{\left(\vec{u}\rho\right)} & =0\\
\pdv{\vec{u}\rho}{t}+\div{\left(\vec{u}\vec{u}\rho+p\Tensor{1}\right)} & =\div{\Tensor{\tau}}+\vec{b}\\
\pdv{E\rho}{t}+\div{\left(\vec{u}E\rho+p\vec{u}\right)} & =\div{\left(\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}-\vec{q}\right)}+\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}+j
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Using the Cartesian tensor index notation, they are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}\begin{bmatrix}\rho\\
u_{1}\rho\\
u_{2}\rho\\
u_{3}\rho\\
E\rho
\end{bmatrix}+\partial_{\alpha}\begin{bmatrix}u_{\alpha}\rho\\
u_{\alpha}u_{1}\rho+p\delta_{\alpha1}\\
u_{\alpha}u_{2}\rho+p\delta_{\alpha2}\\
u_{\alpha}u_{3}\rho+p\delta_{\alpha3}\\
u_{\alpha}E\rho+pu_{\alpha}
\end{bmatrix}=\partial_{\alpha}\begin{bmatrix}0\\
\tau_{\alpha1}\\
\tau_{\alpha2}\\
\tau_{\alpha3}\\
\tau_{\alpha\gamma}u_{\gamma}-q_{\alpha}
\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}0\\
b_{1}\\
b_{2}\\
b_{3}\\
b_{\alpha}u_{\alpha}+j
\end{bmatrix}\label{eq:ConservationLaws3dCartesianTensor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in which, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{t}:=\pdv*{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\alpha}:=\pdv*{x_{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E=e+\frac{1}{2}u_{\alpha}u_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Conservative Differential Form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 smooth for both 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the density of mass, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}$
\end_inset

 operating on an integral can be put inside according to the following rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{}\int_{V}\phi\rho\dd{V}=\int_{V}\DDt{\phi}\rho\dd{V}\label{eq:DDtInsideIntegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Apply the first line of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtOnControlVolume"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Gauss's divergence theorem to the LHS:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\DDt{}\int_{V}\phi\rho\dd{V} & =\int_{V}\pdv{\phi\rho}{t}\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{u}\phi\rho\dd{S}\\
 & =\int_{V}\left(\pdv{\phi\rho}{t}+\div{\left(\vec{u}\phi\rho\right)}\right)\dd{V}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Apply 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtAtPoint"

\end_inset

 to the RHS of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtInsideIntegral"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}\DDt{\phi}\rho\dd{V}=\int_{V}\left(\pdv{\phi}{t}\rho+\vec{u}\rho\cdot\grad{\phi}\right)\dd{V}
\]

\end_inset

Compare these two integrals, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DDtInsideIntegral"

\end_inset

 is true iff
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}\left(\pdv{\rho}{t}+\div{\left(\vec{u}\rho\right)}\right)\phi\dd{V}=0
\]

\end_inset

The integrand is always zero, since the parenthesized term is the LHS of
 the equation for mass conservation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $U=W\rho$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\begin{bmatrix}1 & \vec{u} & E\end{bmatrix}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

.
 So, this lemma can be applied to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationLawsWithDDt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{V}\DDt{W}\rho\dd{V}+\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{P}\dd{S}=\oint_{\partial V}\vu{n}\cdot\vec{G}\dd{S}+\int_{V}H\dd{V}
\]

\end_inset

Again, if the integrands are sufficiently smooth, then Gauss's divergence
 theorem can be applied to them, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\DDt{W}+\div{\vec{P}}=\div{\vec{G}}+H
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\DDt{\rho}=-\rho\div{\vec{u}}\label{eq:ConservationOfMassInNonConservativeForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\DDt{\vec{u}}=\div{\Tensor{\sigma}}+\vec{b}\label{eq:ConservationOfMomentumInNonConservativeForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\DDt{E}=\div{\left(\Tensor{\sigma}\cdot\vec{u}-\vec{q}\right)}+\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}+j\label{eq:ConservationOfEnergyInNonConservativeForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Other Forms of Energy Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equation for Kinetic Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take inner product of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationOfMomentumInNonConservativeForm"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{u}\cdot\rho\DDt{\vec{u}}=\vec{u}\cdot\left(\div{\Tensor{\sigma}}+\vec{b}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator, the LHS then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{u}\cdot\rho\DDt{\vec{u}}=\rho\DDt{}\frac{\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

The resulting equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\rho\DDt{\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2}=\vec{u}\cdot\left(\div{\Tensor{\sigma}}+\vec{b}\right)}\label{eq:EquationForKineticEnergy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the formula for the material derivative of kinetic energy per unit mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equation for Internal Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Define the inner product of two tensors as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{A}:\Tensor{B}=A_{ik}B_{ik}$
\end_inset

 and the gradient of velocity as 
\begin_inset Formula $\grad{\vec{u}}:=\vu{e}_{i}\vu{e}_{k}\pdv*{u_{k}}{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\div{\left(\Tensor{\sigma}\cdot\vec{u}\right)}=\vec{u}\cdot\left(\div{\Tensor{\sigma}}\right)+\Tensor{\sigma}:\left(\grad{\vec{u}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subtract 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EquationForKineticEnergy"

\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationOfEnergyInNonConservativeForm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and recall 
\begin_inset Formula $E=e+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\DDt{e}=\Tensor{\sigma}:\left(\grad{\vec{u}}\right)-\div{\vec{q}}+j
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like any tensor with rank two, the gradient of velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{i}u_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed as a symmetric component 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{ik}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\noun on
strain rate tensor
\noun default
, plus an asymmetric component 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{ik}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\noun on
vorticity tensor
\noun default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pdv{u_{k}}{x_{i}}=\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\pdv{u_{k}}{x_{i}}+\pdv{u_{i}}{x_{k}}\right)}_{E_{ik}}+\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\pdv{u_{k}}{x_{i}}-\pdv{u_{i}}{x_{k}}\right)}_{\Omega_{ik}}
\]

\end_inset

or equivalently
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\grad{\vec{u}}=\Tensor{E}+\Tensor{\Omega}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Tensor{\sigma}:\left(\grad{\vec{u}}\right)=\Tensor{\sigma}:\Tensor{E}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Tensor{1}:\Tensor{E}=\div{\vec{u}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apply them together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Tensor{\sigma}=-p\Tensor{1}+\Tensor{\tau}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Tensor{\sigma}:\left(\grad{\vec{u}}\right)=\Tensor{\tau}:\Tensor{E}-p\div{\vec{u}}
\]

\end_inset

The equation for internal energy then becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\rho\DDt{e}=\Tensor{\tau}:\Tensor{E}-p\div{\vec{u}}-\div{\vec{q}}+j}\label{eq:EquationForInternalEnergy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equation for Entropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationOfMassInNonConservativeForm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=1/\rho$
\end_inset

, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\div{\vec{u}}=\rho\DDt{v}
\]

\end_inset

Move it to the LHS of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EquationForInternalEnergy"

\end_inset

 and recall the 1st law of thermodynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:1stLawOfThermodynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\rho T\DDt{s}=\Tensor{\tau}:\Tensor{E}-\div{\vec{q}}+j}\label{eq:EquationForEntropy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the equation for entropy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Bernoulli's Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The surface force term in the energy equation, i.e.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConservationOfEnergyInNonConservativeForm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\div{\left(\Tensor{\sigma}\cdot\vec{u}\right)} & =\div{\left(\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}\right)}-\div{\left(p\vec{u}\right)}\\
 & =\div{\left(\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}\right)}-\vec{u}\cdot\grad{p}-p\div{\vec{u}}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

in which,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\vec{u}\cdot\grad{p} & =\DDt{p}-\pdv{p}{t}\\
p\div{\vec{u}} & =\frac{p}{\rho}\DDt{\rho}=p\rho\DDt{}\frac{1}{\rho}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Substituting them back into the energy equation and collecting all the 
\begin_inset Formula $\DDt{}$
\end_inset

 terms leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\DDt{}\left(e+\frac{\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}}{2}+\frac{p}{\rho}\right)=\pdv{p}{t}+\div{\left(\Tensor{\tau}\cdot\vec{u}-\vec{q}\right)}+\vec{b}\cdot\vec{u}+j
\]

\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{b}=\grad{\phi}$
\end_inset

, the flow is steady and ignore heat source and heat conduction, it becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\DDt{}\left(h+\phi+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2\right)=0}\label{eq:BernoulliEquationInDifferentialForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the differential form of Bernoulli's equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the flow is 
\emph on
isentropic
\emph default
, there is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\dd{s}=\dd{h}-v\dd{p}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BernoulliEquationInDifferentialForm"

\end_inset

 can be integrated along any 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
trajectory line, e.g.
 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, which gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\int_{p_{1}}^{p_{2}}v\dd{p}+\phi+\abs{\vec{u}}^{2}/2=\text{const}\qquad\forall\vec{x}\in C}\label{eq:BernoulliEquationInAlgebraicForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

